Matrix metalloproteinases"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF)\u003C/strong\u003E is the key initiating signal for angiogenesis. When tissues become hypoxic, they release VEGF which binds to receptors on endothelial cells, triggering the cascade of events that leads to new vessel formation.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMatrix metalloproteinases\u003C/strong\u003E - These enzymes break down extracellular matrix to allow vessel sprouting but act downstream of VEGF\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet-derived growth factor\u003C/strong\u003E - Important for recruiting pericytes to stabilise new vessels but not the primary initiating signal\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransforming growth factor beta\u003C/strong\u003E - Plays a role in vessel maturation and stabilisation rather than initiation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasic fibroblast growth factor\u003C/strong\u003E - Can promote angiogenesis but is not as potent or specific as VEGF\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVEGF triggers endothelial cells to proliferate, migrate, and form new vessel tubes. This process is tightly regulated and requires the coordinated action of multiple growth factors and enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) is the primary signal that stimulates formation of new blood vessels from existing vessels.","Angiogenesis requires degradation of basement membrane, endothelial cell proliferation, and formation of new vessel tubes.","Hypoxia induces VEGF production through hypoxia-inducible factor 1-alpha to promote new vessel growth."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2n